President Joe Biden has announced his intent to nominate Reuben Brigety as Ambassador Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary to the Republic of South Africa. Brigety currently serves as an Adjunct Senior Fellow for African Peace and Security at the Council on Foreign Relations. He has previously held various roles in the State Department, including Deputy Assistant Secretary for Population, Refugees and Migration, Deputy Assistant Secretary for African Affairs, U.S. Ambassador to the African Union, and U.S. Permanent Representative to the United Nations Economic Commission for Africa. Brigety has a background in international affairs and is a member of the American Academy of Diplomacy.

MaryKay Carlson has been nominated as Ambassador Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary to the Republic of the Philippines. She is currently serving as the Deputy Chief of Mission at the U.S. Embassy in Buenos Aires, Argentina. Carlson has extensive experience in the Foreign Service, having served in various diplomatic missions in countries such as India, China, Ukraine, Hong Kong, Mozambique, Kenya, and the Dominican Republic. She has received numerous performance awards throughout her career.

Elizabeth Shortino has been nominated for the position of United States Executive Director of the International Monetary Fund. She has over 17 years of experience in public service, including positions at the Office of Management and Budget, the Department of Treasury, and the Office of the U.S. Executive Director at the International Monetary Fund. Shortino has a background in political science and international relations, with a specialization in quantitative methods and economic theory. She has previously worked as a management consultant and currently resides in Arlington, Virginia with her family.